The principal feature of COPD is limitation of airflow that is not fully reversible. Remodelling of the small-airway compartment and loss of elastic recoil by emphysematous destruction of parenchyma result in progressive decline of FEV1, inadequate lung emptying on expiration, and subsequent static and dynamic hyperinflation.22 At the pathological level, exposure to smoke leads to infiltration of the mucosa, submucosa, and glandular tissue by inflammatory cells. Increased mucus content, epithelial-cell hyperplasia, and disturbed tissue repair with wall thickening in the small conducting airways are cardinal features of COPD (figure 1
).23 This progressive narrowing, obliteration, and even removal of the terminal bronchioles is accompanied by emphysema, which typically starts in the respiratory bronchioles.24 The mechanisms that lead to thickening of the small-airway walls and destruction of lung tissue are far from understood,23 but they are likely to be multifactorial pathobiological processes25 that are interacting on a complex background of genetic determinants,26 lung growth,14 and environmental stimuli (figure 2
).3, 13 Within this framework we discuss the pathogenesis of COPD as a progressive immunological disorder.27
